    <segment id="1" parent="18" relname="span">
I am in complete agreement with Myth #4.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="16" relname="span">  Usability is NOT just common sense :)</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="15" relname="span">  First 
off, common sense in any person has very few absolutes.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="12" relname="contrast">  For example, someone or 
several persons who design an interface may design it according to their own idea 
of &apos;common sense.&apos;</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="8" relname="circumstance">  However, when any other users use the interface,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="13" relname="span"> he/she may be 
completely lost and have no idea what anything means.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="17" relname="span">  Usability, in my opinion, follows 
a very discrete pattern of logic, not to be confused with common sense,</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="10" relname="antithesis"> because 
common sense seems to indicate &apos;not having to think,&apos;</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="14" relname="span"> while logic is simple reasoning 
processes that can be easily identifiable and decided upon.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration">  The key is finding that 
universal logic (not an easy thing to do), or as close as you can.</segment>
